article.headline: Zolman's attitude changes as shots start to fall

article.linkText: Reserve freshman gets hot hand for No. 4 Tennessee
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Shanna Zolman hated Memorial Gym when
she saw it for the first time during practice this weekend. Not
anymore.

<photo1>

	   The Tennessee freshman reserve scored 20 points, including four
3-pointers, and Kara Lawson had 26 as No. 4 Tennessee rallied
from a 16-point deficit to beat No. 17 Vanderbilt 81-67 Sunday
night for its ninth consecutive victory.

	   ''I hated it because it wasn't a good shooting gym. I changed my
mind on that one today,'' said Zolman, who was 4-for-7 from 3-point
range in a gym where the baskets hang out from two extended posts
and team benches are on the end lines.

	   Zolman helped the Lady Vols (18-3, 7-0 Southeastern Conference) improve to 39-6 in
this series with their instate rival by scoring 10 of the first 13
points in the second half to turn a 37-34 halftime deficit into a
41-37 lead they never lost.

	   ''Shanna Zolman today took a lot of pressure off everyone,''
Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said.

	   Vanderbilt (13-7, 3-4) looked ready to beat Tennessee for a
second consecutive year on its home court as the Commodores opened the
game by shooting 61 percent from the floor. They led 25-9 midway
through the first half.

	   The Commodores lost their shooting touch at the break, opening
the second half by not hitting a shot through the first five
minutes. They hit just 39 percent compared to Tennessee, which shot
60 percent in the second half.

	   Vandy coach Melanie Balcomb said her Commodores could not match
Tennessee's depth, and they lost their edge after losing their
intensity on defense.

	   ''It was like we were trying to outscore them, and we needed to
shut them down,'' she said.

	   Tennessee kept building its lead as the Commodores hurried
shots, and the Lady Vols led 71-55 with 5:44 left. Vandy never got
closer than nine the rest of the way.

	   Senior center Chantelle Anderson led Vanderbilt with 21 points,
but she dislocated her right big toe 11 minutes into the game and
was never quite the same as she had only three rebounds. Ashley
McElhiney added 16.

	   Anderson said her foot kept her from running the floor as well
but admitted her biggest problem came when Tennessee unexpectedly gave her room to shoot in the second half.

	   ''As a good player, you need to adjust and take your time
adjusting to what the defense is doing. I didn't do that soon
enough,'' she said.

	   McElhiney said the Commodores, who have lost four of their last
seven SEC games, quit playing defense and helped the Lady Vols
rally.

	   ''They're Tennessee. They're not going to lay down. Every player
on that team is good. We knew that from the beginning,'' she said.

	   Vandy managed a near-even split of the 11,401 fans for a second
consecutive year, but it wasn't enough. The Lady Vols have helped
Vandy bring in nine of its top 10 crowds, and their orange-wearing
fans made Memorial Gym very cozy even when they trailed early.

	   It was much better than Balcomb expected after being warned to
prepare for a hostile crowd.

	   ''I was proud of how much black and gold I saw and how vocal our
crowd was. I thought it was a great environment for a women's
college basketball game,'' Balcomb said.

	   The Vandy students might have hurt their cause by constantly
jeering and taunting Lawson. The senior talked back, but did the
most damage by hitting all five of her 3s.

	   ''Now I know who she was listening to,'' Summitt said. ''I'd
say, 'No,' and she'd launch that 3. She was listening to the
fans.''

	   The teams swapped the lead six times the first five
minutes. Tennessee's last lead of the first half came at 8-6 when
Vandy went on a 19-1 run started by a pair of 3s from McElhiney and
Abi Ramsey.

	   Not even losing Anderson for five minutes to the toe injury
slowed the Commodores. They led 21-9 when she went down at 11:14
and built the lead to 25-9 on another bucket by McElhiney.

	   The Lady Vols would not go away as Lawson scored 13 points in
the half, including a drive with 36.1 seconds left that pulled them
to 37-34 at halftime.
